description: A placeholder name commonly used in programming examples. It often appears alongside 'bar' and 'baz'.
The act of performing a series of seemingly unrelated and tedious tasks that must be done before a particular goal can be achieved.
A method of debugging code by explaining it, line-by-line, to an inanimate object like a rubber duck.
A practice in which two programmers work together at one workstation, with one typing and the other reviewing the code as it is written.
The practice of tracking and managing changes to software code. Popular systems include Git and Subversion.
A principle of software development that stands for 'Don't Repeat Yourself', aiming to reduce repetition of code patterns.
The process of restructuring existing code without changing its external behavior to improve its readability, maintainability, or performance.
A project management and software development approach that emphasizes flexibility, collaboration, and customer feedback.
Stands for Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment, which are practices that aim to improve software quality and delivery speed.
A surface indication that usually corresponds to a deeper problem in the codebase.
